### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.

With the [AuthenticationProperties.ExpiresUtc in JwtHandler](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/32248) by @BrennanConroy, the '_exp_' claim is used in SignalR for expired authentication and closing connections. It will be available in .NET 6 preview 5.

The following has been implemeted for a Blazor Server project (Individual Accounts Authentication Type) to determine if the user is no longer authorized based on the idea of @javiercn : https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/21726#issuecomment-627434195

The Identity User has a ExpirationUtcDateTime property. It is used to define an ExpirationUtcDateTime claim in an additional User Claim principal factory.

```C#
public class AdditionalUserClaimsPrincipalFactory : UserClaimsPrincipalFactory<...>
{
   ...
   public override async Task<ClaimsPrincipal> CreateAsync(WebBiobankUser user)
  {
	// The supplementary claim is added during the clain definition
	var principal = await base.CreateAsync(user);
	var identity = (ClaimsIdentity)principal.Identity;
	var claim = new Claim(nameof(ExpirationUtcDateTime), user.ExpirationUtcDateTime...);
	identity?.AddClaim(claim);
	return principal;
  }
}
```
The expiration is set when logging.

```C#
// When logging
...
user.ExpirationUtcDateTime = DateTime.UtcNow.AddSeconds(...);
...
await _signInManager.SignInAsync(user, new AuthenticationProperties
{
    AllowRefresh = false,
    IsPersistent = false,
    ExpiresUtc = DateTime.UtcNow.AddSeconds(...)
});
```

There is a claim comparison in the authentication state provider with the date with the current time to determine if the user is no longer authorized.

```C#
public class RevalidatingIdentityAuthenticationStateProvider<TUser> : ...
{
   ...
   protected override async Task<bool> ValidateAuthenticationStateAsync(AuthenticationState authenticationState, 
   CancellationToken cancellationToken)
  {
     ...
     // Check is made with the ExpirationUtcDateTime claim information
     ...
  }
}
```

### Describe the solution you'd like
What about a claim with a specific name in the authenticated principal in SignalR to check for expired authentication and closing connections ? Does it make sense ?

I am building an e-commerce website, the users can add items to their cart that is persisted in the DB or local storage. If the user is logged-in the cart items will be saved into the DB, but if the user is not logged-in (anonym) so the cart items are saved into local storage. I already implemented `ProtectedLocalStorage` in a shared class library and all cart operations are working perfectly.

### The project arch.
My project has multiple subdomains;
 - Main shopping site: (e.g. https://www.my-shopping-site.com) where all the products are listed and where users can add items to their shopping carts.
 - Checkout Site: (e.g.: https://checkout.my-shopping-site.com) a subdomain of the shopping site, where the users can view their cart details, and increase/decrease or remove items from their carts.

When an anonym user adds item to the cart, the items is being saved into the local storage relevant to the main shopping site. When the user want to review the cart and do checkout, he is being redirected to the checkout subdomain where the cart items are listed, and there additional increase/decrease of items should be possible.

### The problem
When we are in the subdomain we can't access the local storage of the main website, and that makes it impossible to view the cart items from the subdomain. 

### The desired solution
Add a `BaseDomian` configuration param to the `ProtectedLocalStorage` to define the main site of local storage, so we van access it from subdomains as well. e.g.:

````cs
private readonly ProtectedLocalStorage LocaStorage;

public Foo(ProtectedLocalStorage localStorage)
{
    LocalStorage = localStorage;

    // Define a param for base domain, so even when we do a request from subdomain
    // it will fetch the local storage of the base domain.
    LocalStorage.BaseDomain = "https://my-shopping-site.com";
}
````

### Additional context
A [similar discussion](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4026479/use-localstorage-across-subdomains) was around since many years, but it would be great if we can just do it with a simple setup using `ProtectedLocalStorage`.

